{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> προοίμι-ον</b>, τό, <br /> Trag. <i>contraction</i> <b>φροίμιον</b> (see. below): (οἶμος):— <b>opening, introduction;</b> in Music, <b>prelude, overture,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.4 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in <i>Epic dialect</i> poems, <b>proëm, preamble,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “N.” 2.3, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 1343 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in speeches, <b>exordium,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Critias Philosophus, Tragicus, Elegiacus 43 at Title Page, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1414b19, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.56S., “Stoicorum Veterum Fragmenta” 2.96, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; προοιμίοις ἡδονῆς with <b>prefaces</b> about pleasure, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.27. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i> of <b>any prelude</b> or <b>beginning,</b> φροίμιον χορεύσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 31, compare 829 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; φροιμίοις [δυσφροιμίοις][<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 1216, compare “Th.” 7 \">Refs</a>]; λόγους.. μηδέπω 'ν προοιμίοις only just <b>beginning,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Pr.” 741 \">Refs</a>]; εἴ τι τοῦδε φ. ματᾷ any part of this <b>presage,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Eu.” 142; ὁρῶ τάδε φροίμια.. πόνων [prev. author] “Supp.” 830 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 568, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 4.2.3; ἐγχέων π. 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 78; π. δείπνου 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 110.3; π. ἔχθρας 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 22.4.15; ἀρχῆς [prev. author] 25.3.8 (_plural_); δάκρυά μοι τὰ π. τῆς τέχνης 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Somn.” 3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of <b>premonitory symptoms</b> of disease, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Oribasius Medicus “Synopsis” 8.2. \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>hymn</b> or <b>short poem,</b> such as those attributed to Homer, Ἀπόλλωνος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.104, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 60d, “R.” 531d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φροίμιον Ἀντιλόχου (perhaps Ἀρχιλόχου) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Fragmenta” 223. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8904","accentedUnicode":"προοίμιον","shortDef":"a retort","mediumDef":"a retort","stepGloss":"a retort","stepTransliteration":"prooimion","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}